<br>
You make a valid point regarding the &quot;exp penalty&quot; for hybrids, yet there are some things which I don't think you've really factored in.<br>
<br>
Ok, Bards get Ambidex, and only have double attack w/o dual wield, so in essence, they're paying the same rate for less effective attacks.  This is true, yet, they're paying the same rate for the same percentage power increase as anyone else is.  Ambidex increases a bard's melee power at the same rate as it does a warrior/monk or anyone else.  It is an increase in percentage of current skills as much as it is for anyone.<br>
<br>
Certainly one can make the claim that it takes less total AA points to acheive a similar level of power on one side of the &quot;melee/caster&quot; coin for pure classes than Hybrids, yet we've seen that the truth is that in most cases (With the exception of perhaps SK's/Beastlords) there is adquate compensation in the &quot;special class&quot; skills, and that the total jump in relative power for each hybrid class is much more significant than the jump in power for non wizard specialist classes.<br>
<br>
In other words, one can argue that the ease of acquisition of AA points is significant for hybrids after a &quot;critical mass&quot; is reached, whereas the same argument cannot be made for specialists (particularly warriors).   <br>
<br>
A Ranger pays the same for Ambidexterity, and acheives the same net result as a warrior.  A ranger hits EQ and AM3 and he can exponentially increase the level of advancement at this point.   The same with Paladins and SCM3/SU.   The same cannot be said for warriors with any of their class skills.  There is no exponential increase in power on the inverse with class skills for rogues/monks or warriors.<br>
<br>
What this means is that there IS a payoff for the extra points spent, it's true for pretty much all hybrids (with the possible exception of shadowknights and beastlords), and it's also true for the corresponding non payoff of the &quot;pure&quot; classes.<br>
<br>
I think that the reason for this isn't because VI hates this class or that, but there's things that you can do with Archery for rangers, or Undead for Pallies which make sense in a RP sense, so they added em, whereas there wasn't much you could do for warriors which was unique, as everyone who can wield a weapon can melee.  They didn't really try to institute new things for he pure melee classes, and I really don't think that they tested the AA skills *properly*.  What I mean by properly is sure, you can recreate encounters, but you cannot determine whether class changes are beneficial/detrimental without longer term feedback.  <br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the currrent imbalances occurred outside of what was able to be properly tested, which is drops.   Equipment screwed this game up particularly for warriors, and I'm sure it was done with good intentions of seeing more people able to equip good stuff, and in response to the constant complain in Kunark &quot;Waa melee get good stuff...waa warriors get good stuff&quot;.<br>
<br>
